	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I, a druid, have spent hours kiting these beasts at level 47.  The best strategy<BR>
I have seen are for shamans and necros with pets who root, fear, and have the<BR>
pet(s) attack at will.  They can kill the giant within a few feet of its spawning area.<BR>
<BR>
I always fight the ones in the front and not the one in the back.  The second one<BR>
will not agro on you if you are attacking one so don't worry about that.<BR>
<BR>
The best idea is to be in wolf form because they will not agro you at all and neither<BR>
will anything else (useful for sitting down to med).  Tundra Jack does not attack<BR>
me in wolf form.<BR>
<BR>
For me though the strategy is a little different.  Druids, this should apply to you.<BR>
<BR>
I highly recommend full mana or at least 85-90% (for soloing).  In a group you<BR>
can get by with 50%.  Grouping with a shaman works great.<BR>
<BR>
I start off with an ensnare.  95% of the time it holds but it can be resisted at times.<BR>
If your ensnare is resisted just take off running out towards the tundra and stop<BR>
when you hit the first peak.  Cast ensnare again and it should stick.<BR>
<BR>
Start the IG off with your best DOT spell and then get a good enough distance to<BR>
start nuking away.  Use fire DD spells.  Hit him with three and then DOT again.  Nuke<BR>
three more times.  DOT again.  By this time he should stop moving.  If he is<BR>
ensnared and not rooted you can go up and melee if you want or just sit down and <BR>
start medding while he slowly dies.<BR>
<BR>
Once he's dead you have about ten minutes until the next one pops.  By that time<BR>
assuming you have used most of your mana (like I do) you will still need to med for<BR>
about five minutes before you can fight again.<BR>
<BR>
The loot is very good but at times really odd.  I've gotten as low as four gold and<BR>
no loot - geez what a joke!  I'd say the average is around 25 pp and you almost always<BR>
get a fine steel weapon.  The experience is very good even into the high 40s.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
</table><br>
